gomodel:SYNGO_4812  a     owl:Ontology ;
        rdfs:comment      "Rationale: Figure 3c: InSyn1 coimmunoprecipitates with gephyrin (GPHN) when coexpressed in human embryonic kidney 293 (HEK293) cells.\n\nFigure 4: depletion of InSyn1 leads to significant reduction in mIPSC frequency (i.e. abnormal synaptic inhibition).\n\nWe annotate against a more generic ontology term for now as the exact role of InSyn1 in the inhibitory postsynapse remains unclear. Authors suggest: \"The mechanism of reduced mIPSC frequency for InSyn1 is likely through the disruption of the ability of InSyn1 to form complexes with both gephyrin and the dystrophin complex at the iPSD. Loss of dystrophin might also lead to a secondary trans-synaptic effect on presynaptic release probability through its ability to bind neurexins (22, 23).\". Experimental description: M&M: \"GABAAR-mediated miniature inhibitory postsynaptic currents (mIPSCs) were recorded from CA1 pyramidal cells in hippocampal slices that were biolistically transfected with GFP, spCas9, and validated InSyn1 guide RNA (gRNA) (Fig. 4B).\"\n\nM&M: \"HA-InSyn1 (NM_176921)\" -->> confirms selected uniprot record" ;
        lego:modelstate   "production" ;
        dc:contributor    "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-2286-1587" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-4973-5732" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-2514-0216" ;
        dc:date           "2022-09-01" ;
        dc:title          "SYNGO_BP_4812" ;
        pav:providedBy    "https://syngo.vu.nl" ;
        biolink:in_taxon  "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCBITaxon_10090" .

